nteen. Fed Policy in 2008: A Case of Self-Induced Paralysis? -- tChapter Eighteen. A Confession of Contractionary Effect -- tChapter Nineteen Schadenfreude on the Titanic -- tChapter Twenty Alternative Explanations of the Great Recession -- tPart VI What Does It All Mean? -- tChapter Twenty-One Policy Implications of Market Monetarism -- tChapter Twenty-Two Why Should You Believe in Market Monetarism? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs it possible that the consensus around what caused the 2008 Great Recession is almost entirely wrong? It’s happened before. Just as Milton Friedman and Anna Schwartz led the economics community in the 1960s to reevaluate its view of what caused the Great Depression, the same may be happening now to our understanding of the first economic crisis of this century. Foregoing the usual relitigating of the problems of housing markets and banking crises, renowned monetary economist Scott Sumner argues that the Great Recession came down to one thing: nominal GDP, the sum of all nominal spending in the economy, which the Federal Reserve erred in allowing to plummet. The Money Illusion is an end-to-end case for this school of thought, known as market monetarism, written by its leading voice in economics. Based almost entirely on standard macroeconomic concepts, this highly accessible text lays a groundwork for a simple yet fundamentally radical understanding of how monetary policy can work best: providing a stable environment for a market economy to flourish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMonetary policyzUnited States. 0aRecessionsxEffect of monetary policy onzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook packag